, United Kingdom":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Keir, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Keir, Dumfriesshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1403–1466":"1403–1466","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1402–1413":"1402–1413","1412–Male":"1412–Deceased","1399–1471":"1399–1471","1415–Female":"1415–Deceased","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1270–1292":"1270–1292","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1471":"1471","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1413":"1413","1402":"1402","1445":"1445","1412":"1412","1466":"1466","1400":"1400","1399":"1399","Dunblane, Perthshire, ScotlandScotland, United Kingdom":"Dunblane, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Stirling Castle, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Keir, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Keir, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cunningham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the province of Cunningham in Ayrshire, first recorded in 1153 in the form <i>Cunegan</i>, a Celtic name of uncertain origin. The spellings in <i>-ham</i>, first recorded in 1180, and in <i>-ynghame</i>, first recorded in 1227, represent a gradual assimilation to the English placename element <i>-ingham</i>.","Irish: surname adopted from Gaelic <b>Ó Cuinneagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunigan","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish or Irish   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Conahan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac.","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Connachaín</b> (see   Cunningham  )."]},{"name":"Conaghan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Fergal.","Scottish (Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire) Irish (Donegal): from <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b>, see   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cuningham","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cummingham","meanings":["(1997: 117;2007: 199; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish: variant of   Cunningham  ."]},{"name":"Cunnigham","meanings":["(2007: 429; 2010: NA)","Scottish and Irish (Donegal): variant of   Cunningham  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Cunningham was born in 1403, in Keir, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Gilbert de Cunningham, was 133 and her mother, Anne, was 133. She married Sir William Stirling, 1st of Keir in 1445, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1466, in Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1403–1466":"1403–1466","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1402–1413":"1402–1413","1412–Male":"1412–Surnud","1399–1471":"1399–1471","1415–Female":"1415–Surnud","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1270–1292":"1270–1292","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1471":"1471","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1413":"1413","1402":"1402","1445":"1445","1412"